The Years of the Locusts in Latin America
Misery continues to accumulate in Latin America these days.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is eroding, and political instability is growing.
This is not surprising given that the vast majority of Latin American countries have gone nowhere over the last twenty years.
Capital has been sold off and national debts have soared disproportionately, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
Ces années ont vraiment été mangées par les sauterelles.
Au cours des 20 dernières années, la croissance annuelle du PNB par habitant en Amérique Latine a atteint la moyenne de 0,35 %.
A cette vitesse, une économie mettrait 200 années à doubler.
En Asie, le niveau de vie double chaque décennie.
Avec une croissance tellement anémique, comment l'Amérique Latine peut-elle espérer rivaliser dans le commerce mondial à part à travers une hausse des salaires toujours timide ?
The economic stagnation is a result of bad governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more – a region made up of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors placed it on this path.
First, in the rush to privatize, everything from public services to manufacturing industries was put up for auction.
For a brief moment, the sales of capital helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues derived from privatization produced little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national buyers exhausted all available credit lines.
Other countries did not reach the level of Argentina, but solvency represents a problem in virtually all Latin American countries.
Secondly, given that reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disenchanted.
The inflow of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing, so did the wealth.
No sane politician would engage in another decade of structural reforms that would exhaust the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma signals the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that worked according to technocratic lines and considered economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats are no more.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents keep succeeding each other.
Institutions are being brought to their knees, property rights are questioned, and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is on the way.
Peru and Venezuela are not much luckier; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Luiz Inácio da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls in the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of Latin America's population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic thinking and politics that capital is already starting to flee - even though the elections are still months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks landing hard.
Regarding all the good news about Mexico's fledgling democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low saving rate endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the economically telling result because where there is little saving, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now laments the fat years of the 1970s of OPEC -- years to which it did not belong, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that sold their assets and borrowed rather than save.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market, and the population is well educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
The rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
We cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP is only half that of Brazil.
But with a regional coastal China growing at around 15% per year, can anyone seriously doubt that within the next 15 years it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first due to the massive flow of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to disintegrate: governments are reversing reforms and the economy is losing ground to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely behind us.
We should thus expect even worse economic, social, and political developments in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem—a once again presidential candidate in Argentina—may seem like a bad joke, but anyone concerned with the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
